{{italic title}} [[File:Stebbins-48-Atalanta.jpg|thumb|Photographed by [[Nathaniel Stebbins]] in 1887]] [[File:RESTAURADOR, Olaf Rahardt.jpg|thumb|RESTAURADOR, Olaf Rahardt]] '''''Atalanta''''' was a 228-foot [[steam yacht]] built in [[Philadelphia]] by [[William Cramp & Sons]] in 1883 for the financier [[Jay Gould]]. It was sold to the [[Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela|Venezuelan navy]] in 1900 where it served as the gunboat ''Restaurador'' (Restorer). It was captured by the [[Imperial German Navy|German navy]] during the [[Venezuelan crisis of 1902–03]] and put into service under a German flag as part of the blockading squadron. After the crisis, it was returned to the Venezuelans. It was renamed the ''General Salom'' and continued in service until 1950.<ref name=NYT/>
