'''One Tambon One Product''' ('''OTOP''') is a local [[entrepreneurship]] stimulus program designed by [[Thailand]]'s former Prime Minister [[Thaksin Shinawatra]] during his 2001-2006 [[Thai Rak Thai]] government. The program aimed to support locally made and marketed products of each of Thailand's 7,255 [[tambon]]s (sub-district). Drawing its inspiration from [[Japan]]'s successful [[One Village One Product movement|One Village One Product]] (OVOP) program,<ref>{{cite web|title=What is OTOP?|url=https://www.thaiembassy.sg/friends-of-thailand/p/what-is-otop|website=Royal Thai Embassy Singapore|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Thaitrakulpanich|first1=Asaree|title=DESIGNERS TAKE OTOP PRODUCTS FROM NOPE TO DOPE|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/featured/2017/08/14/designers-remake-otop-products-nope-dope/|accessdate=15 August 2017|work=Khaosod English|date=2017-08-14}}</ref> the OTOP program encourages village communities to improve the quality and marketing of local products, selecting one superior product from each tambon to receive formal branding as its "starred OTOP product". It provides both a local and national stage to the promote these products. OTOP includes a large array of local products, including traditional handicrafts, cotton and silk garments, pottery, fashion accessories, household items, and foods. After a [[CDRM|military junta]] overthrew Thaksin's government in 2006 following an election cancelled for irregularities, the OTOP program was cancelled. However, it was soon revived and rebranded.
The One Tambon One Product movement is a self-help effort wherein rural communities participate in the creation of a product that can be sold locally and internationally.<ref name="Kasem Bundit">{{cite journal|last1=Khongsawatkiat|first1=Kittiphun|title=Isan Studies: 'One Tambon, One Product'; A Government Policy Recovers Farmers' Debts and Fragile Rural Sector in Northeastern of Thailand|journal=Kasem Bundit|date=Jul–Dec 2002|volume=3|issue=2}}</ref>
==Management and organization== OTOP is managed by the Community Development Department (CDD) of Thailand's [[Ministry of Interior (Thailand)|Interior Ministry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.cdd.go.th/en/related-links/%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A0%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%99-en/about-us|website=Community Development Department (CDD)|publisher=Ministry of Interior|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref>
There are 36,000 OTOP groups in Thailand, each having between 30 to 3,000 members. Sakda Siridechakul, president of [[Chiang Mai Province|Chiang Mai]]'s OTOP association noted, "OTOP has helped spread income to many people in the villages. It has allowed people producing [[handicrafts]] to feel they are part of the global economy."{{CN|date=August 2017}}
==Financials== In 2017 OTOP product sales were 153 billion [[Thai baht|baht]]. The government aims for sales of 200-300 billion baht every year.<ref name=BP-20180515>{{cite news|last1=Wancharoen|first1=Supoj|title=Villages go all out to charm tourists|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1465542/villages-go-all-out-to-charm-tourists|accessdate=15 May 2018|work=Bangkok Post|date=15 May 2018}}</ref>
The government allocated 8.3 billion baht budget to the CDD to stimulate community tourism in 3,273 villages across the country between April–September 2018. Among the program's aims are to develop at least 64,570 new OTOP items with an average annual sales growth of at least 10 percent.<ref name=BP-20180515/>
==After the 2006 coup== The [[CDRM|military junta]] that [[2006 Thailand coup|overthrew]] the Thai Rak Thai government on 19 September 2006 changed the program's name to ''Local and Community Products'', but OTOP branding was kept.{{CN|date=August 2017}}
==OTOP Product Champion== One of the mechanisms to promote and support the development of Thai OTOP products is the "Product Champion" (OPC). Besides setting up OTOP communities and small to medium enterprises (SME), a seminar called "Smart OTOP" has now provided more than 26,600 participants advice in improving their skills and knowledge in order to develop better products. The number of participants increases each year.{{CN|date=August 2017}}
A rating system for OTOP products is followed, the highest being five stars. At last count, there were 569 five-star products.<ref>{{cite web|title=OTOP 5 Star Products|url=http://www.otop5star.com/index-en.php|website=OTOP5Star|publisher=Community Development Department|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref>
There is an annual exhibition of products called "OTOP Mid-year". OTOP Mid-year-2010 ended with consolidated turnover of 810 million [[Thai baht|baht]].<ref>http://thainews.prd.go.th/en/news.php?id=255308300044</ref>{{failed verification|date=August 2017}}
