'''Philip Bayard "Phil" Crosby''', (June 18, 1926 – August 18, 2001) was a businessman and author who contributed to management theory and quality management practices.<ref> {{cite web |url = http://www.wppl.org/wphistory/PhilipCrosby/index.html |title = Philip Crosby Collection |publisher = Winter Park Public Library |accessdate = 2009-05-02 |year = 2004 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090429015921/http://www.wppl.org/wphistory/PhilipCrosby/index.html |archivedate = 2009-04-29 |df = }} </ref>
Crosby initiated the [[Zero Defects]] program at the [[Glenn L. Martin Company|Martin Company]].<ref name="Harwood"/> As the quality control manager of the [[Pershing missile]] program, Crosby was credited with a 25 percent reduction in the overall rejection rate and a 30 percent reduction in scrap costs.
==Early life and career== Crosby was born in Wheeling, West Virginia, in 1926. He served in the Navy during World War II and again during the Korean War. In between, he earned a degree from the [[Kent State University College of Podiatric Medicine|Ohio College of Podiatric Medicine]].<ref name="PCA"/>
His first job in the field of quality was that of test technician in the quality department at [[Powel Crosley, Jr.|Crosley Corporation]] in [[Richmond, Indiana]] beginning in 1952. He left for a better-paying position as [[Reliability engineering|reliability engineer]] at [[Bendix Corporation]] in [[Mishawaka, Indiana]] in 1955, working on the [[RIM-8 Talos]] missile. He left after less than two years to become senior quality engineer at [[Glenn L. Martin Company|The Martin Company]]'s new [[Orlando, Florida]] organization to develop the [[Pershing missile]]. There he developed the [[Zero Defects]] concept.<ref name="Harwood">{{cite book | last = Harwood | first = William B. | title = Raise Heaven and Earth: The Story of Martin Marietta People and Their Pioneering Achievements | year = 1993 | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | location = [[New York City|New York]] | isbn = 9780671749989 | oclc = 28710737 | page = 350 | chapter = 27: "Zero Defects" Was Invented Here | quote = Zero Defects was the brainchild of a gifted and articulate young engineer named Philip Crosby, who conceived it while working as quality control manager on Pershing.}}</ref> He eventually rose to become department head before leaving for [[ITT Corporation]] in 1965 to become director of quality.
==Philip Crosby Associates== In 1979, Crosby started the [[management consulting]] company Philip Crosby Associates, Inc.<ref name="PCA"/> This consulting group provided educational courses in quality management both at their headquarters in [[Winter Park, Florida]], and at eight foreign locations. Also in 1979, Crosby published his first business book, ''Quality Is Free''. This book would become popular at the time because of the crisis in North American quality. During the late 1970s and into the 1980s, North American manufacturers were losing market share to Japanese products largely due to the superior quality of the Japanese goods.
Crosby's response to the quality crisis was the principle of ''"doing it right the first time"'' (DIRFT). He also included four major principles:<ref name="Creech">{{cite book | last = Creech | first = Bill | authorlink = Wilbur L. Creech | title = The Five Pillars of TQM: How to Make Total Quality Management Work for You | year = 1994 | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press|Truman Talley Books]] | location = [[New York City|New York]] | isbn = 9780525937258 | oclc = 28508067 | page = 478 | chapter = 11: A TQM Path to Tomorrow: New Ways for New Days}}</ref> :#''The definition of quality is conformance to requirements (requirements meaning both the product and the customer's requirements) :#''The system of quality is prevention :#''The performance standard is [[zero defects]] (relative to requirements) :#''The measurement of quality is the [[Quality costs|price of nonconformance]]
His belief was that an organization that establishes good quality management principles will see savings returns that more than pay for the cost of the quality system: "quality is free". It is less expensive to do it right the first time than to pay for rework and repairs.
